  "title": "Talking About Money and Asking for Prices (Levantine)",
  "dialect": "levantine",
  "steps": [
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Money (General Term)"
        },
        "text": "In Levantine Arabic, the most common word for 'money' is مَصاري (maSaari). You might also hear نُقود (nuqood), which is more formal.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "مَصاري",
            "english": "Money",
            "transliteration": "maSaari"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "نُقود",
            "english": "Money (formal)",
            "transliteration": "nuqood"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Currency Units"
        },
        "text": "The main currency unit in many Levantine countries is the 'Lira' (لِيرَة), pronounced 'leera'. Another common currency is the 'Dinar' (دِينار), pronounced 'deenaar'.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "لِيرَة",
            "english": "Lira",
            "transliteration": "leera"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "دِينار",
            "english": "Dinar",
            "transliteration": "deenaar"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Asking 'How much money?'"
        },
        "text": "To ask 'How much money?' in general, you use كَمّ مَصاري؟ (kam maSaari?). كَمّ means 'how much/many'.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "كَمّ مَصاري؟",
            "english": "How much money?",
            "transliteration": "kam maSaari?"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "practice-sentence",
      "sentence": {
        "arabic": "معي مَصاري قليلة.",
        "english": "I have little money.",
        "transliteration": "ma'i maSaari qaleeleh."
      },
      "context": "Using the general term for money."
    },
    {
